  "summary": "Shelley Beck visits Gladys Dixon, who is working on a paper pattern in a small bedroom. Gladys mentions suffering from indigestion and shares news from the movie company. She reports that Marina Gregg has returned to the set and caused a disturbance by complaining that her coffee tasted wrong. Gladys explains that she serves Marina coffee in a specific ceramic cup, but Mr. Rad resolved the issue by pouring the coffee down the sink. Shelley suggests that Marina may be the target of assassination attempts, noting the presence of threatening letters and a previous incident where a marble statue fell from a pedestal in a room called \"Short Brown,\" nearly striking the actress.\n\nGladys expresses a desire to quit her job at the movie company's restaurant, fearing that an assassin might strike a bystander. She recalls an incident involving Heather, suggesting that Heather may have spilled her navy blue nylon taffeta cocktail dress on purpose. Gladys expresses interest in the dress and plans to visit the mansion to speak with the Italian butler, Mr. Zucco, though Shelley suspects Gladys's true motive is to see him.\n\nMeanwhile, Miss Marple discusses the murder case with Dr. Hedlock while knitting. Miss Marple concludes that if the cocktail was tampered with, the drug must have been administered in a way that no one witnessed, despite the presence of eighteen to twenty people. Dr. Hedlock suggests the possibility that the drug might have been pre-placed in an eye-drop bottle.",
